<subSubSection pageId="33" pageNumber="34" type="diagnosis">
<paragraph blockId="33.[151,1437,1153,1610]" pageId="33" pageNumber="34">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[199,321,1261,1286]" pageId="33" pageNumber="34">Diagnosis.</emphasis>
Belongs to the 
<taxonomicName box="[501,646,1262,1285]" class="Insecta" family="Nepticulidae" genus="Stigmella" kingdom="Animalia" order="Lepidoptera" pageId="33" pageNumber="34" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="marmorea">
<emphasis box="[501,646,1262,1285]" italics="true" pageId="33" pageNumber="34">S. marmorea</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
species group. The combination of two white to cream fasciae on the forewing and numerous large cornuti on the vesica distinguishes 
<taxonomicName box="[879,1023,1298,1321]" class="Insecta" family="Nepticulidae" genus="Stigmella" kingdom="Animalia" order="Lepidoptera" pageId="33" pageNumber="34" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="marmorea">
<emphasis box="[879,1023,1298,1321]" italics="true" pageId="33" pageNumber="34">S. marmorea</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
from all other 
<taxonomicName box="[1190,1295,1297,1322]" class="Insecta" family="Nepticulidae" genus="Stigmella" kingdom="Animalia" order="Lepidoptera" pageId="33" pageNumber="34" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="genus">
<emphasis box="[1190,1295,1297,1322]" italics="true" pageId="33" pageNumber="34">Stigmella</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
species.
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
<subSubSection pageId="33" pageNumber="34" type="description">
<paragraph blockId="33.[151,1437,1153,1610]" pageId="33" pageNumber="34">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[199,260,1333,1358]" pageId="33" pageNumber="34">Male</emphasis>
(
<figureCitation box="[274,357,1333,1358]" captionStart="FIGURE 33" captionStartId="13.[151,250,1943,1965]" captionTargetBox="[159,1431,207,1912]" captionTargetId="figure@13.[151,1436,193,1922]" captionTargetPageId="13" captionText="FIGURE 33. Adults of the central Andean Nepticulidae." httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/556881/files/figure.png" pageId="33" pageNumber="34">Fig. 33</figureCitation>
). Described in 
<bibRefCitation author="Puplesis" box="[525,826,1333,1358]" pageId="33" pageNumber="34" refString="Puplesis, R. &amp; Robinson, G. S. (2000) A review of the Central and South American Nepticulidae (Lepidoptera) with special reference to Belize. Bulletin of the Natural History Museum, London (Entomology), 69 (1), 1 - 114." type="journal article" year="2000">Puplesis &amp; Robinson 2000</bibRefCitation>
: 26–27. Forewing length: 4.0– 
<quantity box="[1167,1255,1333,1358]" metricMagnitude="-3" metricUnit="m" metricValue="4.6" pageId="33" pageNumber="34" unit="mm" value="4.6">4.6 mm</quantity>
; wingspan: 9.0– 
<quantity box="[151,254,1370,1394]" metricMagnitude="-2" metricUnit="m" metricValue="1.01" pageId="33" pageNumber="34" unit="mm" value="10.1">10.1 mm</quantity>
.
</paragraph>
<paragraph blockId="33.[151,1437,1153,1610]" box="[199,599,1405,1430]" pageId="33" pageNumber="34">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[199,293,1405,1430]" pageId="33" pageNumber="34">Female.</emphasis>
Externally similar to male.
</paragraph>
<paragraph blockId="33.[151,1437,1153,1610]" box="[199,911,1441,1466]" pageId="33" pageNumber="34">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[199,376,1441,1466]" pageId="33" pageNumber="34">Male genitalia.</emphasis>
Illustrated in 
<bibRefCitation author="Stonis" box="[533,746,1441,1466]" pageId="33" pageNumber="34" refString="Stonis, J. R., Diskus, A., Remeikis, A., Gerulaitis, V. &amp; Karsholt, O. (2016 d) Leaf-mining Nepticulidae (Lepidoptera) from record high altitudes: documenting an entire new fauna in the Andean paramo and puna. Monograph. Zootaxa, 4181 (1), 1 - 94. http: // doi. org / 10.11646 / zootaxa. 4181.1.1" type="journal article" year="2016" yearSuffix="d">
Stonis 
<emphasis box="[609,658,1441,1466]" italics="true" pageId="33" pageNumber="34">et al</emphasis>
. 2016d
</bibRefCitation>
: figs 125–127.
</paragraph>
<paragraph blockId="33.[151,1437,1153,1610]" box="[199,968,1477,1502]" pageId="33" pageNumber="34">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[199,403,1477,1502]" pageId="33" pageNumber="34">Female genitalia.</emphasis>
Illustrated in 
<bibRefCitation author="Puplesis" box="[559,862,1477,1502]" pageId="33" pageNumber="34" refString="Puplesis, R. &amp; Robinson, G. S. (2000) A review of the Central and South American Nepticulidae (Lepidoptera) with special reference to Belize. Bulletin of the Natural History Museum, London (Entomology), 69 (1), 1 - 114." type="journal article" year="2000">Puplesis &amp; Robinson 2000</bibRefCitation>
: fig. 210.
</paragraph>
<paragraph blockId="33.[151,1437,1153,1610]" box="[199,926,1513,1538]" pageId="33" pageNumber="34">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[199,330,1513,1538]" pageId="33" pageNumber="34">Bionomics.</emphasis>
Adults fly in February. Otherwise biology unknown.
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
